-- pg_turbovec v1.19.0 -- all index reads through the buffer manager.
--
-- This file is a *reference mirror*. The authoritative install
-- script is generated by `cargo pgrx schema`.
--
-- v1.19.0 removes the direct relfile mmap. ALL index data is now read
-- through PostgreSQL's shared-buffer cache (ReadBufferExtended) --
-- there is no mmap/pread of the relfile. This is the correct posture
-- for managed/sandboxed Postgres and any environment that restricts
-- direct file access; the buffer manager is the single source of
-- truth for page reads (consistent pinning/locking, clean crash +
-- streaming-replication semantics).
--
-- READ-PATH change only:
--   * The whole-load scan reads the blocked codes / rotation chains
--     via the buffer manager (the path that was already the mmap
--     fallback).
--   * Out-of-core IVF serving is PRESERVED without mmap: the
--     cell-scoped gather reads ONLY the probed cells' code pages
--     through the buffer manager (relfile::gather_codes_ranges), so
--     the resident set stays O(probes * cell_size), not O(n).
--   * turbovec.mmap_static_blocked is now a DEPRECATED no-op, kept
--     for one minor so an existing SET does not error; it is ignored
--     and will be removed in a future minor.
--
-- There is NO wire-format change (MetaPageData::version unchanged),
-- NO SQL surface change, and NO REINDEX. Warm queries are unchanged
-- (the prepared index is cached per-backend). The cost given up is
-- cold-fill speed and double-cache avoidance on an index larger than
-- shared_buffers; size shared_buffers to hold the (compressed) hot
-- index -- pg_turbovec's 7-15x compression makes that practical.
-- See docs/BUFFER_CACHE_ONLY_DESIGN.md.
--
-- `ALTER EXTENSION pg_turbovec UPDATE TO '1.19.0';` resolves against
-- this intentionally-empty file.
